1303","1255":"1255","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1273":"1273","1272":"1272","about 1297":"about 1297","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Lwydiarth, Montgomershire, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Bole House, Glovers Meaton Bradeley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Llewllyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Jenkin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal names <i>Jankin</i>, <i>Jenkin</i>, and <i>Jonkin</i>, pet forms of <i>Jan</i>, <i>Jen</i>, and <i>Jon</i> + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-kin</i>. In Middle English, names in <i>-kin</i> were often used to name the younger of two family members with the same personal name."],"variants":[{"name":"Jenkins","meanings":["English and Welsh: variant of   Jenkin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. <i>Jenkins</i> is one of the most common surnames in England, especially southwestern England, but is also especially associated with Wales."]},{"name":"Jenks","meanings":["English (West Midlands): from the Middle English personal name <i>Jenke</i> (a shortening of the personal name <i>Jenkin</i>, <i>Jankin</i>; see   Jenkin  ), with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","History: Joseph Jenks (1602–83), the descendant of an old Welsh family, was born in England and traveled to Saugus, near Lynn, MA, in 1642 to assist in the development of America's first iron works. His son, Joseph Jenckes (sic), followed in 1650, founded Pawtucket, RI, and raised four sons who held places of respect and distinction in RI, including one who served as governor for five years."]},{"name":"Jenkinson","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): from the Middle English personal names <i>Jankin</i>, <i>Jenkin</i>, or <i>Jonkin</i> (see   Jenkin  ) + <i>son</i>."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joyce verch Llewllyn Jenkin was born about 1273, in Wales, United Kingdom, her father, Jenkin ap Llewellyn, was 20 and her mother, Gwenhwfar verch Ieuan Gethyn, was 20. She married Humphrey Wever ap Ieuan about 1297, in Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1375, in Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 103."},"et":{"circa 1273–1375":"umbes 1273–1375","1273–1375":"1273–1375","1272–1303":"1272–1303","1303–1365":"1303–1365","1255–Male":"1255–Surnud","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","12 December 1365":"12. detsember 1365","1303":"1303","circa 1273":"umbes 1273","about 1303":"umbes 1303","1255":"1255","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1273":"1273","1272":"1272","about 1297":"umbes 1297","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lwydiarth, Montgomershire, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Bole House, Glovers Meaton Bradeley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"circa 1273–1375":"noin 1273–1375","1273–1375":"1273–1375","1272–1303":"1272–1303","1303–1365":"1303–1365","1255–Male":"1255–Kuollut","1255–Female":"1255–Kuollut","12 December 1365":"12. joulukuuta 1365","1303":"1303","circa 1273":"noin 1273","about 1303":"noin 1303","1255":"1255","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1273":"1273","1272":"1272","abo